I have evaluated the critiques and implemented a refinement to the current best model (`bayesian_diagnosticity`) to address the significant discrepancy observed regarding the **`max_run_penalty`**.

### Explanation of the Cognitive Hypothesis
The critique highlighted that the current models, including `bayesian_diagnosticity`, under-penalize large maximum runs compared to actual human judgments. The standard "motif" process models continuations linearly in log-space (i.e. as a standard Markov process). I refined this by positing an *accelerating* (squared) expectation penalty for long streaks under the regular/alternative hypothesis. This reflects the cognitive heuristic that real randomness avoids extremely long streaks, and that sequences containing them are perceived as intentionally generated by a process deliberately producing anomalous localized streaks. 

I have written this hypothesis into `hypothesis.md` and successfully translated it into a valid PyMC model in `candidate.py`.

The candidate has passed the required self-check and evaluates safely. I have also cleaned up the test scripts from the working directory.
